---
import { withBase } from '../../lib/url';
import Prose from '../../layouts/Prose.astro';
import QuoteList from '../../components/QuoteList.astro';
import { TECHNIQUES } from '../../lib/techniques';

const t = TECHNIQUES.find((x) => x.slug === 'modes-of-perfection')!;
---

<Prose
  title={t.title}
  description={t.description}
  crumbs={[{ name: 'Techniques', href: '/techniques/' }, { name: t.title }]}
  kicker="Technique"
  jsonLd={[{ '@type': 'Article', headline: t.title }]}
>
  <p>
    In the house chart, a question is answered by the relation between the figure of the querent
    (normally the first house) and the figure of the thing asked about (the house of the
    quesited). The medieval geomancers (the doctrine is set out most systematically in the
    <em>Method of Judging Questions</em> that circulated under the name of Pietro d'Abano)
    recognised four principal ways the chart <em>perfects</em>, that is, joins querent to
    quesited and promises the matter accomplished:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Occupation</strong>: the same figure stands in the house of the querent and the
      house of the quesited: the matter is achieved without impediment.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Conjunction</strong>: the figure of the querent or of the quesited passes to a
      house immediately beside the other: the matter is achieved by effort; whose figure moves
      shows who must do the seeking.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Mutation</strong>: the figures of querent and quesited appear together, side by
      side, elsewhere in the chart: the matter is accomplished, but in an unexpected way or place.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Translation</strong>: a third figure appears next to both significators: the matter
      is accomplished through a go-between, another person or thing answering to that figure.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If the chart shows none of these (and no aspect joins the significators) the matter is
    denied. The favourableness of the figures themselves then colours <em>how</em> the thing comes
    about, for which see <a href={withBase('/figures/')}>the natures of the figures</a> and
    <a href={withBase('/techniques/aspects-and-company/')}>their aspects and friendships</a>.
  </p>
  <p class="sourcing">
    The summary above follows the pseudo-Abano
    <a href={withBase('/library/abano/method-of-judging-questions/')}>Method of Judging Questions</a>.
    Cattan teaches the same doctrine under his own names (<em>occupation</em> and the
    <em>company of conjunction</em>) with worked examples from his own practice:
  </p>
  <QuoteList topic="perfection" />
</Prose>

<style>
  .sourcing {
    font-family: var(--font-ui);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-ink-muted);
  }
</style>
